# The Fraud Triangle (1951)

&gt; Hypothesis: “Trusted persons become trust violators when they conceive of themselves as having a financial problem which is non-sharable, are aware that this problem can be secretly resolved by violation of the position of financial trust and are able to apply to their own conduct in that situation verbalisations which enable them to adjust their conceptions of themselves as trusted persons with their conceptions of themselves as users of entrusted funds or property.”&lt;sup&gt;1, 2&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; Donald R. Cressey, Why Do Trusted Persons Commit Fraud? A Social-Psychological Study of Defalcators, Journal of Accountancy, 92 (1951), 576 – 581.

&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; Donald R. Cressey, Other People’s Money: A Study in the Social Psychology of Embezzlement, Free Press, 1953, at page 973.
]

---

# The Fraud Triangle studies

* Interviewed 133 inmates in three prisons for his study&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;;

* Three elements present in every fraud: motivation (some kind of perceived pressure), opportunity ( some perceived opportunity) and rationalisation (some way to rationalise the fraud as not being inconsistent with one’s values.)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;.

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; Donald R. Cressey, Why Do Trusted Persons Commit Fraud? A Social-Psychological Study of Defalcators, Journal of Accountancy, 92 (1951), 576 – 581.

&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; Donald R. Cressey, Other People’s Money: A Study in the Social Psychology of Embezzlement, Free Press, 1953, at page 973.
]

---

# The Fraud Triangle: Motivation

* Motive (or pressure or incentive)

* Feel a pressure or a need to commit fraud, e.g. financial obligations;

* “fraud pressure” = “perceived non-shareable financial need”.

* “status deflating” = the embarrassment of not being able to fulfil the financial need.

---

# The Fraud Triangle: Opportunity

* An open door for solving a non-shareable problem in secret by violating a trust;

* Concealment;

* Would not get caught;

* Some technical skill and knowledge of the systems and controls within an organisation;

* Directors and managers represent a high fraud risk is because their rank in hierarchical organisations often gives them the ability to override controls.

---

# Rationalisation: morally acceptable rationalisation

* Before the crime takes place

* Convince himself or herself that the actions they are about to take are not really criminal at all

* A conscious decision by the perpetrator to place his or her needs above the needs of others;

* Preserving his or her self-image as a trustworthy person;

* Some common rationalisations (the act is justified): . . . ;

---

# Some common rationalisations:

* Even up the scorecard;

* Promotion that was not forthcoming;

* Pay rise inadequate;

* No expected bonus;

* Just a loan;

* Company does not need money;

* Part of general scheme in which they are not completely culpable;

---

