# Profile of a fraudster

* [2010 Association of Certified Fraud Examiner (ACFE) Report to the Nations](http://bit.ly/2dMaFwX)

    + The greatest risk lies at the top

    + Tenure

    + The squeezed middle

    + The fraudster’s department 

---

# The greatest risk lies at the top

* They are the individuals with the greatest opportunity to commit fraud by overriding controls

* They are likely to have the ability to conceal the fraud too

* Biggest fraud losses tend to result from the actions of well-educated, older males

---

# Tenure

* Those working for a longer period of time tend to generate more trust from their managers and peers

* They can develop a good understanding of the systems and procedures, being in a position to spot weakness and evade internal controls

* They may reach higher levels of authority

---

# The squeezed middle

* The typical internal fraudster in the UK is a male middle manager in his thirties who has been employed by the victim organisation for between three and five years

* Middle managers remain longer at that level because of poor economy

* The middle manager (highly-skilled technical) perceives that his or her superior has an inadequate grasp of the technical detail

---

# The fraudster’s department

* Accounting, operations, sales, customer service, purchasing and executive / upper management

* Working on the trading desks of financial services institutions

* The executive suite (board and senior management level) as one of the high-risk departments

