# Offence of fraud

---

# Fraud Act 2006

* [Fraud Act 2006](http://bit.ly/1vsRnMz). What is the offence of fraud since 15 January 2007

* A single primary offence of fraud, contained in section 1 of the Fraud Act 2006.

* The offence can be committed in 3 different ways:

    + by a false representation (section 2);

    + by a failure to disclose information when there is a legal duty to do so (section 3);
  
    + by abuse of a position (section 4).

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; Harrison &amp; Ryder, The Law Relating to Financial Crime in the United Kingdom, 2nd edition. Chapter 4: Fraud
]
---
  
# Some secondary offences including:

* possession or control of articles for use either in the course of or in connection with frauds (section 6);

* making, adapting, supplying or offering to supply articles for use in frauds (section 7);

* participating in fraudulent trading as a sole trader (section 9);

* obtaining services dishonestly where the defendant either intends not to pay or not to pay in full (section 11).

---

# Fraud by false representation (section 2)

* Dishonestly made a false representation; AND

* Intended by making that false representation:

    + make a gain (for themselves or any other person); OR
  
    + cause or expose an individual to the risk of a loss.

---

# Fraud by false representation (section 2)

* Offender focused and a conduct crime

&gt; “The offence is entirely offender focused; as long as a false representation is actually made and the requisite dishonest intention element exists, the offence is made out. There is no need, therefore, to prove that an actual gain or loss was achieved, making this offence a conduct crime rather than a result crime . . . .”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; Harrison &amp; Ryder, The Law Relating to Financial Crime in the United Kingdom, 2nd edition. Chapter 4: Fraud
]

---

# Fraud by false representation (section 2)

* What is a representation

* A representation is “any representation, implied or expressed (can be made through an omission), as to fact or law, including a representation as to the state of mind of:”

    + “the person making the representation; or
  
    + any other person.”

---

# False representation to a machine?

* If a person makes a false representation to a CHIP and PIN device or ATM machine, does he commit the offence of fraud contrary to the Fraud Act 2006?

* What if gives false credit card details to the voice activated software on a telephone lie?

* What if gives false credit card details to a supermarket website to obtain groceries?

---

# False representation to a machine? (section 2(5))

* Yes, in UK

&gt; “. . . a representation may be regarded as made if it (or anything implying it) is submitted in any form to any system or device designed to receive, convey or respond to communications (with or without human intervention).”

---

# Fraud by false representation (section 2)

* False? (section 2(2))

* “Representations are deemed to be false when they are:”

    + ““misleading or untrue”; AND

    + the defendant knows or thinks this to be the case.”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; Harrison &amp; Ryder, The Law Relating to Financial Crime in the United Kingdom, 2nd edition. Chapter 4: Fraud
]

---

# Knowledge of defendant:

&gt; “A person may have reasonable grounds to suspect that property is one thing (A) when in fact it is something different (B). But that is not so when the question is what a person knows. A person cannot know that something is (A) when in fact it is (B). The proposition that a person knows that something is (A) is based on the premise that it is true that it is (A). The fact that the property is (A) provides the starting point. Then there is the question whether the person knows that the property is (A).” - [R v Montila (Steven William) (2004) 1 WLR 3141](http://bit.ly/2dVPAxE)

---

# Defendant knows the representation is “misleading or untrue”

&gt; The proposition that a person (defendant) knows that something (the representation) is (A) (“misleading or untrue”) is based on the premise that it is true that it (the representation) is (A) (“misleading or untrue”). So, it is necessary to prove that the representation is misleading or untrue.&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; Harrison &amp; Ryder, The Law Relating to Financial Crime in the United Kingdom, 2nd edition. Chapter 4: Fraud
]

---

# Dishonesty: 

* R v Ghosh [1982] 1 QB 1053

&gt; “. . . a jury must first of all decide whether according to the ordinary standards of reasonable and honest people what was done was dishonest. If it was not dishonest by those standards, that is the end of the matter and the prosecution fails. If, however, it was dishonest by those standards, then the jury must consider whether the defendant himself must have realised that what he was doing was by those standards dishonest. ”

---

# Dishonesty

* [Ivey (Appellant) v Genting Casinos (UK) Ltd t/a Crockfords (Respondent) [2017] UKSC 67](http://bit.ly/2zCiYD8)

* 25 October 2017

&gt; However, the second leg of the rule adopted in Ghosh has serious problems. The principal objection is that the less a defendant’s standards conform to society’s expectations, the less likely they are to be held criminally responsible for their behaviour. The law should not excuse those who make a mistake about contemporary standards of honesty, a purpose of the criminal law is to set acceptable standards of behaviour.&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Press Summary, The Supreme Court, 25 October 2017](http://bit.ly/2gPMIJ5)
]

---

# Dishonesty

* [Ivey (Appellant) v Genting Casinos (UK) Ltd t/a Crockfords (Respondent) [2017] UKSC 67](http://bit.ly/2zCiYD8)

* 25 October 2017

&gt; In civil actions the law has settled on an objective test of dishonesty. There can be no logical or principled basis for the meaning of dishonesty to differ according to whether it arises in a civil action or a criminal prosecution. The second leg of the test propounded in Ghosh does not correctly represent the law and directions based upon it ought no longer to be given. The test of dishonesty is that used in civil actions. The fact-finding tribunal must ascertain (subjectively) the actual state of the individual’s knowledge or belief as to the facts and then determine whether his conduct was honest or dishonest by the (objective) standards of ordinary decent people. There is no requirement that the defendant must appreciate that what he has done is, by those standards, dishonest.&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Press Summary, The Supreme Court, 25 October 2017](http://bit.ly/2gPMIJ5)
]


---

# Fraud by failing to disclose information (section 3)

* Lying by omission

&gt; “The defendant must have dishonestly failed to disclose to another person information that they were under a legal duty to disclose and by this failure intended to make a gain for themselves or another, or cause a loss or the risk of a loss to another.”

* Offender focused and a conduct crime

&gt; “. . . the offence is offender focused with it being unnecessary to prove either that someone was misled or that a loss or gain was actually made.”

---

# Fraud by failing to disclose information (section 3)

* Extent and nature of legal duty

&gt; “Section 3 makes it an offence to commit fraud by failing to disclose information to another person where there is a legal duty to disclose the information. A legal duty to disclose information may include duties under oral contracts as well as written contracts. The concept of “legal duty” is explained in the Law Commission’s Report on Fraud, which said at paragraphs 7.28 and 7.29:”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Explanatory Notes to Fraud Act 2006](http://bit.ly/2dFc2jc)
]

---

# Extent and nature of legal duty

&gt; “7.28 . . . Such a duty may derive from statute (such as the provisions governing company prospectuses), from the fact that the transaction in question is one of the utmost good faith (such as a contract of insurance), from the express or implied terms of a contract, from the custom of a particular trade or market, or from the existence of a fiduciary relationship between the parties (such as that of agent and principal).”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Explanatory Notes to Fraud Act 2006](http://bit.ly/2dFc2jc)
]

---

# Extent and nature of legal duty

&gt; “7.29. For this purpose there is a legal duty to disclose information not only if the defendant’s failure to disclose it gives the victim a cause of action for damages, but also if the law gives the victim a right to set aside any change in his or her legal position to which he or she may consent as a result of the non-disclosure. For example, a person in a fiduciary position has a duty to disclose material information when entering into a contract with his or her beneficiary, in the sense that a failure to make such disclosure will entitle the beneficiary to rescind the contract and to reclaim any property transferred under it.”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Explanatory Notes to Fraud Act 2006](http://bit.ly/2dFc2jc)
]

---

# Extent and nature of legal duty

&gt; “For example, the failure of a solicitor to share vital information with a client within the context of their work relationship, in order to perpetrate a fraud upon that client, would be covered by this section. Similarly, an offence could be committed under this section if a person intentionally failed to disclose information relating to his heart condition when making an application for life insurance.”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Explanatory Notes to Fraud Act 2006](http://bit.ly/2dFc2jc)
]

---
# Extent and nature of legal duty

&gt; “The information that is not disclosed does not have to be material or relevant; there is no de minimis provision and it is not a defence to claim ignorance of the duty or incompetence in supplying information.”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Explanatory Notes to Fraud Act 2006](http://bit.ly/2dFc2jc)
]
---

# Fraud by abuse of position (section 4)

* Offence by omission and positive act

&gt; “The defendant must occupy a position ‘in which he is expected to be safeguard, or not act against, the financial interests of another person’; they must dishonestly abuse this position; and through this abuse intended to either make a gain for themselves or another or cause a loss or risk the causing of a loss.”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Law Reform Commission on Fraud](http://bit.ly/2dR9BIy)
]

---

# Fraud by abuse of position (section 4)

* Offender focused and a conduct crime

&gt; “This can also be carried out through omission rather than by a positive act. Also, as with the other two offences, this too is offender focused.”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Law Reform Commission on Fraud](http://bit.ly/2dR9BIy)
]

---

# Fraud by abuse of position (section 4)

* Position that the defendant must occupy

&gt; “The necessary relationship will be present between trustee and beneficiary, director and company, professional person and client, agent and principal, employee and employer, or between partners. It may arise otherwise, for example within a family, or in the context of voluntary work, or in any context where the parties are not at arm’s length. In nearly all cases where it arises, it will be recognised by the civil law as importing fiduciary duties, and any relationship that is so recognised will suffice. We see no reason, . . . ”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Law Reform Commission on Fraud](http://bit.ly/2dR9BIy)
]

---

#Fraud by abuse of position (section 4)

* Position that the defendant must occupy

&gt; “ . . . We see no reason, however, why the existence of such duties should be essential. This does not of course mean that it would be entirely a matter for the fact-finders whether the necessary relationship exists. The question whether the particular facts alleged can properly be described as giving rise to that relationship will be an issue capable of being ruled upon by the judge and, if the case goes to the jury, of being the subject of directions.”&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; [Law Reform Commission on Fraud](http://bit.ly/2dR9BIy)
]

