# Policy background Policy background

* The UK Government’s policy on the reform of the criminal law of fraud is largely based on the Law Commission’s Report on Fraud (Law Com No. 276, Cm 5560, 2002).

* In 2006, fraud became a major policy goal of the UK Government.

* The Fraud Review concluded that the government has two functions:

    + to protect public money from fraudsters; and
  
    + to protect customers and businesses against fraud.

---

# The Fraud Review

* The Fraud Review recommended creation of:

    + The National Fraud Authority to develop and implement the government strategy;

    + The National Fraud Reporting Centre so that businesses and individuals could report fraud (This resulted in the creation of the National Fraud Intelligence Bureau).

    + a national lead police authority based on the City of London Police.

---

# Objectives of the National Fraud Authority

* To create a criminal justice system that is sympathetic to the needs of the victims of fraud by ensuring that the system operates more effectively and efficiently;

* To attempt to discourage organised criminals from committing fraud in the UK; and

* To increase the public’s confidence in the response to fraud

---

# National Fraud Authority

* Published [National Fraud Strategy](http://bit.ly/2dW0uDH):

    + Tackling the threat of fraud;
  
    + Acting effectively to pursue fraudsters and holding them to account;
  
    + Improving the support available to victims;
  
    + Reducing the UK’s exposure to fraud;
  
    + Targeting acting against fraud more effectively.

---

# UK legislative framework prior to Fraud Act 2006

* 98 offences, including 8 deception offences, created by the Theft Acts of 1968 and 1978;

* The common law offence of conspiracy to defraud

---

# Difficulties of the Theft Acts

* Difficult to enforce;

* Notoriously technical;

* Over-particularised;

* Difficult to interpret;

* Did not meet the need of developing technology including electronic means of transfer.

.footnote[
&lt;sup&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; P. Kiernan and G. Scalan, Fraud and the law commission: the future of dishonesty, (2003) Journal of Financial Crime, 10(3), 199 –208.

&lt;sup&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; D. Ormerold, The Fraud Act 2006 - criminalising lying? (2007) Criminal Law Review, March, 193 – 219.
]

